322 WUTHERING HEIGHTS.

“ ‘Mr. Hareton Wishes you would read to
us, ma’am,’ I said, immediately. ‘ He’d take
it very kind—he’d be much obliged.’

“ She frowned; and, looking up, answered,

“‘ Mr. Hareton, and the whole set of you
will be good enough to understand that I re-
ject any pretence at kindness you have the
hypocricy to offer! I despise you, and will
have nothing to say to any of you! \Vhen I
would have given my life for one kind word,
even to see one of your faces, you all kept off:
But I won’t complain to you! I’m driven
down here by the cold, not either to amuse
you, or enjoy your society.’

“‘What could I ha’ done?’ began Earn-
shaw. ‘ How was I to blame?’

“‘ Oh! you are an exception,’ answered
Mrs. Heathcliﬁi ‘ I never missed such a con-
cern as you.’

“‘But, I offered more than once, and
asked,’ he said, kindling up at her pertness,
‘ I asked Mr. Heathcliff to let me wake for

you—’

